</font> </td></tr><tr><td width='686' height='55' valign='top' align='left'> <font face='Arial,sans-serif' SIZE=2 COLOR=#ffff80> Source: EQVault Network -  </font> <a href=http://www.eqvault.com </a> www.eqvault.com </td></tr><tr><td width='686' height='19' valign='top' align='left'> <font face='Arial,sans-serif' SIZE=2 COLOR=#ffff80> 2000-07-12 - Ester The Tester (Heh?) Says Hello</font> </td></tr><tr><td width='686' height='19'></td></tr><tr><td width='686' height='19' valign='top' align='left'> <font face='Arial,sans-serif' SIZE=2 COLOR=#C0C0C0> <p><span class="newstitle">Ester the Tester Speaks!</span><br>
<span class="newstext">
<blockquote>
  <p>Hello all,<br>
  Theres been a bit of misconceptions lately about the function of our Quality
  Assurance department. One of our QA Reps, affectionatly known as Ester the
  Tester, asked me to post this for her.<br>
  <br>
  -Gordon<br>
  <br>
  --------------------------------<br>
  <br>
  Hello!<br>
  <br>
  Let me introduce myself. I am ‘Ester the Tester’ (yes it rhymes) and I
  have asked Abashi to post a letter from the testing department to all of our
  players. I attended the EQGathering this weekend and spent quite a bit of time
  listening to players concerns. I felt that having Abashi put up a post
  detailing what the testing department is and is not may help the communication
  process between us and you the players.<br>
  <br>
  What we do:<br>
  1. We read each and every email sent to eqtesting@verant.com<br>
  2. We read the bug reports as often as we can<br>
  3. We attempt to the best of our abilities to reproduce the bugs the players
  send us<br>
  4. We assign bugs to the Development Team.<br>
  <br>
  What we do not do:<br>
  1. We do not have creative control over anything in game<br>
  2. We do not continue reading emails if they are abusive or flames<br>
  3. We do not do reimbursals<br>
  4. We do not respond to any emails, if we did this nothing else would get done<br>
  <br>
  <br>
  I would like to list a few things that if included in the emails and bug
  reports that would make it much easier for us to reproduce the situations.<br>
  1. Zone name<br>
  2. Location -- /loc<br>
  3. Full names of NPC’s<br>
  4. Full names of items - not abbreviations, I don’t know all of them!!<br>
  5. Location<br>
  6. Any mitigating circumstances even if they seem trivial (you’d be
  surprised)<br>
  7. Location<br>
  8. Server - even on bug reports, some times they get shuffled<br>
  9. Location<br>
  10. Did I mention Location???<br>
  11. Server name<br>
  12. Location<br>
  <br>
  If you are reporting a broken quest PLEASE include the starting NPC’s full
  name, the zone it is in, the NPC’s loc, and the phrase used to trigger the
  quest. This will save us SO much time when reproducing these bugs.<br>
  <br>
  Something else that is useful is the threads that talk about broken quests, or
  bugs in the game. It is a little difficult to sort out the wish lists, flames,
  complaints, but we have pulled bugs out of those threads and some of them are
  already fixed.<br>
  <br>
  I am a firm believer in communication. I as also a firm believer in EverQuest,
  and the team of testers I work with. There are some things we just don’t
  catch. We haven’t played every class race combination to 60, so we
  desperately need your input. Please remember that the testing department can
  not change anything fundamental in the game, so the rants and flames are a
  waste of your and my time. To be honest, when I get an email that is offensive
  I stop reading right there. It is the same with posts.<br>
  I do lurk on these boards, and I communicate frequently with Abashi. Sometimes
  he will ask for more information and clarification. This is usually me asking
  him to find me some more information so we can reproduce whatever bug you are
  talking about.<br>
  <br>
  Thank you for playing EverQuest and caring so much about this game. I do
  promise to lurk and read. I’ll never post, but if Abashi says Ester the
  Tester said well that was me.<br>
  </p>
</blockquote>
</span>

